@NODE "Reg" "Registration"
@TOC "MAIN"
    Registration
    ------------

    If you use xpkDMCB for more than one month, you *have to*
    register. After using xpkDMCB for more than one month, it
    is both illegal and immoral to use it further!

    I can't (and won't) continue development if I don't get a
    reasonable number of registrations.

    As a registered user, you will get:

    - a personal keyfile

    - a xpkDMCB based CLI file Compression/Expansion utility
      (almost done)

    - a xpkDMCB based library supporting more than one mode,
      which could dramatically increase CF performance
      (in preparation)

    - the DMC exploration kit:
      Choose from different models, find the best compression
      method for various file types, adjust all parameters to
      compress the specific file type most powerful
      (in development)

    - beta-testing pre-releases

    The registration fee for users with e-mail access:
    - 10 DM if you live in Germany
    - 10 $ else

    The registration fee for users without e-mail access:
    - 15 DM if you live in Germany
    - 15 $ else

    Note: I won't accept other currencies.

    Just hide the cash (no coins please!) in an envelope and
    send it to the author's address. See @{" Author " LINK "Aut"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Req" "Requirements"
@TOC "MAIN"
    Requirements
    ------------

    Due to the compression algorithm, DMC uses high system
    resources.
    You need at least:

    - a 68020 or better CPU
    - a FPU (68881/2 or 68040/060)
    - 2097152 bytes RAM (two chunks of 1048576 byte each
      will be allocated)
    - AmigaOS2.0 or higher (because of AllocVec/FreeVec)

    xpkDMCB.library was written in 100% Assembler and was
    tested with CyberGuard and Mungwall during development.
    I have tested it on several hundred files now. It seems
    to work well, but you never know...

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Int" "Introduction"
@TOC "MAIN"
    Introduction
    ------------

    xpkDMCB is a very powerful XPK-based *lossless*
    compression library. Its technique differs from
    Lempel-Ziv-based methods (LZ77 as used in NUKE,
    LZ78 as used in LHA) as well as from Huffman-
    based methods (HUFF, HFMN).

    The method used is called Arithmetic Coding. An
    incoming sequence of bits is represented by a real
    number in the range between 0.0 and 1.0. This real
    number is then written to the output. For more
    detailed information refer to the @{" Literate " LINK "Lit"}.
    Arithmetic coding has been shown to be superior to
    Huffman coding in most cases.

    A model is used to predict the probability of the
    incoming bit to be 0 or 1. This model `remembers'
    bit patterns and when the same pattern occurs more
    often, it is predicted with a very high probability,
    therefore adding only a few bits to the real number.
    Low probability patterns require more bits in the
    output.

    The model used in xpkDMCB is called "braid tree".
    It consumes much RAM, it starts with 65536 nodes
    (each node requires 16 bytes) and expands itself
    until 131072 nodes are reached. Then the model is
    flushed, and it starts again with 65536 nodes.

    Note: Using other models than the braid tree could
    mean much better compression performance. Another
    possibility is to reduce space requirements and
    make a model with very few nodes. I think this
    model mechanism offers very flexible possibilities
    and some other programs will be released soon to
    find out which model works best (see also
    @{" Registration " LINK "Reg"}).

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Ins" "Installation"
@TOC "MAIN"
    Installation
    ------------

    Simply copy xpkDMCB.library into your LIBS:compressors/
    drawer. Don't forget that xpkmaster.library must be
    present in your LIBS: path.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "Usa" "Usage"
@TOC "MAIN"
    Usage
    -----

    Use programs like xpack/xup, xDrop, XpkKnight to
    compress/expand your desired files. I wouldn't
    use xpkDMCB as the standard library for XFH,
    because it is too slow. Use it for backups or
    archives, and check if xpkDMCB isn't worse than
    xpkSHRI, xpkGZIP, xpkSQSH or LZX.

@ENDNODE

